Sir Alex Ferguson is seriously ill in hospital after undergoing emergency surgery for a brain haemorrhage. The former Manchester United manager is reported to have been rushed to hospital from his Cheshire home on Saturday morning. Manchester United said in a statement: “Sir Alex Ferguson has undergone emergency surgery today for a brain haemorrhage. The procedure has gone very well but he needs a period of intensive care to optimise his recovery. His family request privacy in this matter.” His son Darren, who manages Doncaster Rovers, missed his side’s final fixture of the League One campaign on Saturday due to a “severe family issue.” A statement on the club website said: “Darren asks for privacy, and will provide an update through the club during the week.’ Sir Alex went down in history for leading Manchester United to a 13 Premier League titles, five FA Cups, and two Champions League crowns during hisl 27 years the helm at Old Trafford. He retired from management in 2013 and at the time he said: “The decision to retire is one that I have thought a great deal about. It is the right time.” He also wrote the following in his 2015 book, Leading: “Now, after a lifetime of getting ready for work at six in the morning, I like waking up at eight, having breakfast with Cathy (which I had not done for 30 years), reading the paper, and going to have lunch in the village.”